Monks have latched onto the wonderful low weight high ac/+hp all/all items VERANT placed into the game. This, combined with thier other defensive abilities has caused them to become a viable tank class in many situations.<br>
Ideally, warriors should have significantly higher ac / hp.<br>
Monks can get comparable ac / hp with the right gear. This wasn't much of an issue because of the weight penalty to ac for monks, until the advent of the mentioned ac / +hp 0.x wt items.<br>
<br>
What has me concerned is instead of addressing the issue of overpowered low weight items that sidestep a monks inherant ac/weight penalties, they 'balance' the entire class making those same items necessary to be an average monk.<br>
<br>
What I see, both as a monk and a warrior, they screwed up some items and now nerf a  class to balance it.<br>
So two wrongs don't make a right except on Norrath? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/ukhanktinga.showPublicProfile?language=EN>khanktinga</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#FF0000>(10/10/02 7:05:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1386.topic&index=85>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: An open letter to Warriors from a Monk... </span><hr size=1> The core problem with all class balance issues is something fundamental to the game: too many classes, too few roles. There are 6 classes for whom dealing and taking melee damage are central to their 'roles' in the game: Warriors, Knights, Rogues, Monks, and Rangers. (Beastlords and Bards' melee damage is at best half of what those two classes are valued for). There's just no way they'll ever be able to maintain a good balance between those 6 classes and still keep them unique. The pendulum will swing wildly forever between the classes, that's just the way it is.<br>
<br>
As for the monk problem being a gear problem rather than a class one, that's a no brainer. When I think monk, I think of a spiritual bad ass, in a loose and light pair of pants, slippers, and no shirt to show of his totally ripped frame. A  guy (or gal) with such a tight mind/body connection that he could kick your ass with a pair of chop sticks just as easily as the quarterstaff of ownage. But EQ being what it is: a totally item driven game, a character that should disdain material things as a distraction from his spirituality is instead just as reliant as any other class on getting the next better weapon or piece of armor if he wants to improve his fighting abilities.<br>
<br>
My own personal opinion and view of what monks should be, is that toe to toe with a humanoid-type enemy, a monk would be just as hard to kill as any other melee class, warrior included, regardless of armor. Of course, this 'vision' is inherently imbalanced. Quite frankly, that vision has the monk being better than the warrior in most respects, hardly something balanced for a class-based game. <br>
<br>
So we comprimise that ideal to have some kind of trade off. In exchange for the improved damage and special skills and abilities monks get, they are supposed to have the following penalties:<br>
1) be less able to take punishment for long periods of time (less hps)<br>
2) get hit harder when they do get hit (less mitigation)<br>
3)have more limited equipment choices (wt and leather-class items restrictions). <br>
<br>
Without all three of those penalties, monks become too powerful. It's that simple.<br>
<br>
Where did Verant go wrong?<br>
<br>
1) Monks are in the right place on the HP totem pole, IMO.<br>
2) There simply should never be an AC softcap that is so independent of how powerful the mobs are. Having anything over 1300 AC be useless against frogs in OS is fine. At some point you outclass a mob one on one so much that it no longer matters. But to have it mean little to nothing against mobs like Emp, or the AoW is just plain stupid.<br>
3) There should have been MUCH better supervision and oversight of zone designers so that items obviously too powerful for a class that is supposed to have item restrictions were never introduced in the first place. It should have been obvious to anyone that really knows the game that Low wt , high AC items usable by all melee classes, or even all classes would be unbalancing for monks. It had previously been the case that monk usable armor was always much lower in AC than the best armor available to other melee classes, but a few designers got lazy just put in all/all stuff instead of thinking out more logical armor sets.<br>
<br>
The best solutions, again, IMO:<br>
<br>
2) Completely retool the way mitigation is determined. It should compare the player's AC against the mob's attack value, or some other number associated with how powerful the creature is. You could still have 'soft caps' for when the character is so much more powerful than the mob that he is outclassing it in one on one melee when he has a group to support him. (i.e. is getting buffed and healed, has people to debuff the mob, etc.) So, there could still be soft caps for xp groups, or for fighting greens solo, but AC would always matter against the boss mobs. Also, the actual mitigation tables would be different for plate, chain, leather, and cloth classes. Then, having 1400 AC on a wizard could matter, but he would still mitigate less than a warrior with 1000 AC, or something along those lines. This would give the classes that now get hit for max 90% of the time now some more options for equipment, perhaps.<br>
<br>
3) Retro-nerf all/all and all melee/all high-end items that are the best armor pieces for armored melee, and are clearly too high in AC for monks.<br>
<br>
Verant should have some in-house programs that use their melee algorithms to simulate fights and come up with average dps numbers. If they don't, that's really lame. I'm no programmer, but as a scientist that uses custom written programs for simulations and data analysis, I can tell you that such tools would be easy to write for a professional programmer. Such tools would be 10 times more accurate than the best parsed logs. They could then use those tools to determine when they get the adjustments suggested in 2) and 3) right before even putting them on test, let alone on the live servers.<br>
<br>
I'm far from being a monk-basher. Friends in my guild have monks that are about where they should be in terms of tanking ability and damage without this incoming nerf. One friend was already thinking of setting aside his lvl 60 monk because his item upgrade paths required a raiding, powerguild playstyle he just doesn't like. This will put him over the edge, as he's already started to twink and plvl a SK to replace him.<br>
<br>
So, as a warrior, I fully realize that these were all Verant's @#%$ ups, but regardless of how clueless they've been in the past, they need to fix these problems if they want their other games to be half as successful as EQ has been. I for one, simply don't trust them to maintain star wars and EQ2 the way they should be. They will both probably be good games to start with, but eventually, they'll @#%$ them up if history provides any lessons. <p><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=193443" target="_blank">
<img src="http://plaza.ufl.edu/ktinga/eqimages/OlavnBalth2.jpg" border="0">
</a> 

